      Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.Te=
sla & BitcoinApparently someone sat Elon Musk down and told him=C2=A0where =
Bitcoins come from? Yesterday he tweeted:Tesla has suspended vehicle purcha=
ses using Bitcoin. We are concerned about rapidly increasing use of fossil =
fuels for Bitcoin mining and transactions, especially coal, which has the w=
orst emissions of any fuel.Cryptocurrency is a good idea on many levels and=
 we believe it has a promising future, but this cannot come at great cost t=
o the environment.Tesla will not be selling any Bitcoin and we intend to us=
e it for transactions as soon as mining transitions to more sustainable ene=
rgy. We are also looking at other cryptocurrencies that use <1% of Bitcoin=
=E2=80=99s energy/transaction.Elon Musk=E2=80=99s whims are among the main =
drivers of Bitcoin=E2=80=99s price,  so:The largest cryptocurrency dropped =
as much as 15% to just above $46,000, before paring some of the retreat. It=
 was down about 6% to $51,210 as of 7:03 a.m. in London on Thursday. Other =
tokens such Ether and Dogecoin also slid. The rush to sell briefly caused o=
utages at some cryptocurrency exchanges.=C2=A0Look, you know what I think. =
The funny move here would be if Tesla Inc. had dumped all its Bitcoins at t=
he highs. (It  sold about 10% of its Bitcoins in March =E2=80=9Cessentially=
 to prove liquidity of Bitcoin,=E2=80=9D but I suppose that could have been=
 a test run for a larger sale?) And then maybe gone short too for good meas=
ure. And then Elon Musk announces =E2=80=9Coh actually Bitcoin is bad now l=
ol,=E2=80=9D and the price plummets, and he grins his impish grin and we=E2=
=80=99re all like oh, Elon, you got us again.I have no reason to believe th=
at this is what happened, though I note that=C2=A0technically=C2=A0Musk=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0statement says that Tesla =E2=80=9Cwill not be=C2=A0selling an=
y=C2=A0Bitcoin,=E2=80=9D not that it hasn=E2=80=99t already. I=E2=80=99m ju=
st saying,=C2=A0if I=C2=A0was Elon Musk, that=E2=80=99s what I would do. Th=
en of course I=E2=80=99d buy more Bitcoins after the price falls, I=E2=80=
=99d tweet =E2=80=9CBitcoin is great again,=E2=80=9D the price would go up,=
 I=E2=80=99d sell my Bitcoins, I=E2=80=99d tweet =E2=80=9Coh no it=E2=80=99=
s bad again,=E2=80=9D the price would go down, I=E2=80=99d buy more Bitcoin=
s, I=E2=80=99d tweet =E2=80=9Cback to great,=E2=80=9D etc. etc. etc. This w=
ould be vastly more profitable, for Tesla, than making cars, and it would c=
apitalize on Musk=E2=80=99s core skill of trolling people on Twitter. How l=
ong do you think he could keep this up? I think the answer is=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cfar longer than I could remain sane while watching it happen.=E2=80=9D[1=
]=C2=A0Again, though, I don=E2=80=99t think this is what happened; I assume=
 that Tesla has kept most of its Bitcoin stash and is not profiting from Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s tweets. As far as I can tell he has only limited interest in m=
anipulating the price of Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0or Dogecoin, or Tesla stock=
, or the other assets whose prices he can control=C2=A0with his tweets =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0for profit. He=E2=80=99ll do it for fun, sure, occasionally, bu=
t not in a way that serves his rational self-interest. I assume that what a=
ctually happened is pretty much what Musk said: He got into cryptocurrency =
on a whim because it fit with his image of being fun and futuristic and ann=
oying, and then someone explained to him that it doesn=E2=80=99t fit with h=
is image of being good for the environment, and on a whim he decided to coo=
l it on the Bitcoin stuff for a while.=C2=A0And when Elon Musk announces a =
decision on Twitter, he will often  stick with that decision for hours, som=
etimes even days at a time. Surely by next week he=E2=80=99ll be tweeting, =
like, =E2=80=9Cwe are building a giant battery in the desert to mine Bitcoi=
n, Bitcoin is good again, you can use it to pay for Teslas,=E2=80=9D and th=
e price will shoot back up, and I=E2=80=99ll once again hit the button that=
 auto-generates this column.My Bloomberg Opinion colleague Liam Denning  po=
ints out that =E2=80=9CMusk=E2=80=99s move may also indicate that Teslas we=
ren=E2=80=99t flying off the shelves as a result of accepting Bitcoin payme=
nt,=E2=80=9D and in fact it=E2=80=99s not entirely clear whether Tesla has =
sold any cars for Bitcoins.[2] I hope it hasn=E2=80=99t. I hope Musk can ma=
ke the price of Bitcoin go up or down by 10%=C2=A0by announcing that Tesla =
will or will not accept Bitcoins for cars, without ever actually accepting =
any Bitcoins for any cars either way. There=E2=80=99s something pure about =
that: The price of Bitcoin depends on Elon Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0attitude=C2=
=A0toward it, not on the existence of any grubby commercial transactions in=
 which Bitcoins are exchanged for cars.[3] The source of value for Bitcoin =
is not its=C2=A0use as a currency=C2=A0or=C2=A0economic importance; the sou=
rce of value for Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0for everything =E2=80=94=C2=A0is si=
mple proximity to Elon Musk.Anyway, since Musk is looking for alternatives,=
=C2=A0I have a coin that uses <1% of Bitcoin=E2=80=99s energy per transacti=
on!=C2=A0It is called ExcelCoin.[4] Instead of relying on proof-of-work, bu=
rning tons of energy to mine coins to reward people for keeping track of th=
e ledger of transactions, as Bitcoin does, ExcelCoin relies on me keeping t=
rack of the list of transactions in Microsoft Excel. If you want to buy Exc=
